@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "ex9 - POCO Controller";
}

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Welcome to ex9</h1>
    <p>This exercise demonstrates POCO (Plain Old CLR Object) Controllers in ASP.NET Core.</p>
    
    <h2>POCO Controller Routes</h2>
    <p>Click the links below to test the POCO HomeController:</p>
    
    <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
        <li style="margin: 15px;">
            <a href="/home" class="btn btn-primary">/home</a>
            <p><small>Returns: Welcome message</small></p>
        </li>
        <li style="margin: 15px;">
            <a href="/home/today" class="btn btn-info">/home/today</a>
            <p><small>Returns: Current date and time</small></p>
        </li>
        <li style="margin: 15px;">
            <a href="/home/http/123" class="btn btn-success">/home/http/123</a>
            <p><small>Returns: "The ID number is: 123"</small></p>
        </li>
        <li style="margin: 15px;">
            <a href="/home/http/456" class="btn btn-warning">/home/http/456</a>
            <p><small>Returns: "The ID number is: 456"</small></p>
        </li>
        <li style="margin: 15px;">
            <a href="/home/http/789" class="btn btn-secondary">/home/http/789</a>
            <p><small>Returns: "The ID number is: 789"</small></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <hr/>
    <h3>What is a POCO Controller?</h3>
    <p>A POCO (Plain Old CLR Object) controller is a simple C# class that doesn't inherit from <code>Controller</code> or <code>ControllerBase</code>.</p>
    <p>It uses attributes like <code>[Route]</code> and <code>[HttpGet]</code> to define routing and HTTP methods.</p>
    
    <h3>Test Invalid Routes</h3>
    <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
        <li style="margin: 10px;"><a href="/home/invalid">/home/invalid</a> → Invalid route (404 Error)</li>
        <li style="margin: 10px;"><a href="/invalidcontroller">/invalidcontroller</a> → Invalid controller (404 Error)</li>
    </ul>
</div>
